NOTES_AMOS = {
    1: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: Tekoa was a town in Judah approximately 10 miles south of Jerusalem, in the rugged Judean highland. Amos was a noqed (shepherd/sheep-breeder; Strong\'s H5349), possibly a guild-master of livestock, not a mere laborer — the same term is used of Mesha king of Moab in 2 Kgs 3:4. The earthquake mentioned here was apparently so memorable it is referenced again in Zech 14:5, suggesting a catastrophic seismic event ca. 760 BCE that served as a temporal landmark for a generation.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The theophanic roar of YHWH from Zion establishes Jerusalem as the true seat of divine authority, not the northern sanctuaries at Bethel or Dan. The withering of Carmel — renowned for its lush fertility — signals that YHWH\'s judgment overrides the fertility blessings associated with Baal worship prevalent in the north. TYPOLOGY: This image of the divine voice bringing cosmic disruption anticipates the eschatological theophany language of Joel 3:16, which uses nearly identical phrasing, and ultimately the voice of the Son at the final judgment (Heb 12:26).',
        3: 'HEBREW: The refrain "for three transgressions...and for four" (\'al-sheloshah pish\'e...ve\'al-arba\'ah) employs a graded numerical formula common in Wisdom literature (cf. Prov 30:15-31) indicating not a precise count but an overflowing, accumulated fullness of sin — the measure is complete and running over. The word pesha\' (Strong\'s H6588) means a deliberate rebellion or revolt, the strongest Hebrew term for sin as willful transgression. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The formula "I will not revoke it" (lo\' ashivennu) likely refers to the irrevocable divine decree issued from the heavenly council — YHWH\'s judicial sentence, once pronounced before his council, cannot be recalled.',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: "Kir" appears as the place of Aramean origin in Amos 9:7, making this judgment an ironic reversal — exile back to their place of origin. The Valley of Aven ("Valley of Wickedness") may be a deliberate derogatory renaming of the Beqa\'a Valley. Beth-eden ("House of Delight/Eden") was a powerful Aramean city-state on the upper Euphrates, known in Assyrian records as Bit-Adini, conquered by Shalmaneser III in 855 BCE.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The oracle against Gaza indicts the Philistine city-states for trafficking in whole populations — the Hebrew galut shelemah ("a complete/whole exile") points to comprehensive ethnic deportation, likely selling entire Israelite communities into Edomite slave-markets. This is one of the earliest prophetic condemnations of the slave trade, establishing a universal moral order under YHWH that applies even to nations outside the Mosaic covenant.',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: The "covenant of brotherhood" (berit achim) between Tyre and Israel likely refers to the treaty forged between Hiram of Tyre and both David and Solomon (2 Sam 5:11; 1 Kgs 5:1-12). Tyre\'s violation of this covenant by selling Israelite captives to Edom compounds its guilt with betrayal of formal treaty obligations — a grave offense in ancient Near Eastern diplomacy. THEOLOGICAL: That Tyre is held accountable to a covenant it made with Israel demonstrates that YHWH governs international covenantal ethics, not merely Israel\'s internal Torah observance.',
        11: 'HEBREW: The word rahamim (Strong\'s H7356), translated "pity" or "compassion," derives from the root rechem meaning "womb," conveying the most intimate, instinctive form of mercy — the love of a mother for the child of her womb. Edom\'s sin is described as the total suppression of this primal compassion toward his own brother Jacob/Israel. THEOLOGICAL: The perpetual and unrelenting nature of Edom\'s wrath ("his anger tore perpetually, and he kept his wrath forever") contrasts with YHWH\'s own anger which, though real, is described as momentary in comparison to his enduring hesed (Ps 30:5). TYPOLOGY: The Edom oracles throughout the prophets (Obad; Isa 63; Jer 49) develop into an eschatological type of implacable hostility to God\'s people, ultimately transformed in NT perspective where "Edom" becomes a cipher for all anti-kingdom opposition.',
        13: 'HISTORICAL: The atrocity of ripping open pregnant women (biqqa\' haroth) was a recognized war crime in the ancient Near East, attested in Assyrian and other records as a tactic of terrorizing populations and destroying the next generation — it was the ultimate negation of future hope. The motive given — territorial expansion — makes this a prophetic indictment of land-greed as the driving force behind dehumanizing violence. THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s condemnation of Ammon for this act reveals that universal human rights rooted in the imago Dei are enforced by the divine King even among nations who possess no written Torah.',
        14: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "tempest" and "whirlwind" (sa\'ar and suphah) on the day of battle are recurring images of divine-warrior theophany, suggesting that YHWH himself fights against Ammon as a conquering warrior-king (cf. Nah 1:3; Ps 83:15). The day of battle is portrayed as YHWH\'s own day of intervention — a micro-instance of the larger "Day of YHWH" theme that becomes central to the book\'s climax in Amos 5:18-20.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: The burning of the bones of the king of Edom to lime (Hebrew: sid) was an act of extreme desecration in the ancient Near East, denying the dead proper burial and rest. This violated widely-held ANE conventions about the sanctity of royal remains. Notably, Moab\'s crime was against Edom — a non-Israelite nation — demonstrating that YHWH\'s moral governance extends to all peoples, not Israel alone. (Gen 9:6; Rom 2:14-15)',
        3: 'HEBREW: "Shophet" (H8199) here means ruler or judge, the one who governs and dispenses justice. Its cutting off signals total governmental collapse. The stripping of leadership is a recurring covenantal curse form in the prophets. (Deut 28:36; Isa 1:26)',
        4: 'HEBREW: "Torah" (H8451) denotes instruction or law, specifically YHWH\'s revealed teaching given through Moses. "Statutes" (chuqqim, H2706) are the engraved, fixed divine ordinances. Judah\'s sin is not ignorance but willful rejection — a heightened culpability. THEOLOGICAL: That Judah receives the same structural oracle-formula as the pagan nations is striking; possession of the Torah increases, rather than diminishes, accountability before YHWH. (Luke 12:48; Rom 2:17-24)',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The indictment against Israel is the longest and most detailed of all eight oracles, occupying verses 6-16. Selling the righteous (tsaddiq) for silver echoes Joseph\'s betrayal (Gen 37:28) and anticipates the betrayal of the Righteous One for thirty pieces of silver (Matt 26:15; Acts 7:52). TYPOLOGY: The "righteous" sold for silver foreshadows the Messiah, the supremely Righteous One, sold by Judas. (Zech 11:12-13; Matt 27:9)',
        7: 'HEBREW: "Anawim" (H6041) — the afflicted, humble, and oppressed poor — is a theologically loaded term in the Psalter and prophets, often describing those who have no human advocate and thus depend entirely upon YHWH. (Ps 9:12; 37:11; Matt 5:5) THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "profane my holy name" (chalal, H2490, + shem qodshi) shows that social injustice is not merely an ethical failure but an act of sacrilege — a desecration of YHWH\'s very character revealed in Israel. (Lev 22:2; Ezek 36:20-23)',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: The Amorites are described with gigantic stature ("like the height of the cedars"), echoing the Nephilim/Rephaim traditions associated with the pre-conquest inhabitants of Canaan. (Num 13:32-33; Deut 3:11) DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Amorites represent peoples allotted to the jurisdiction of other divine beings (Deut 32:8-9), yet YHWH\'s power overwhelms these territorial arrangements to secure Israel\'s inheritance — their destruction is both historical and cosmically significant. (Deut 32:8; Josh 24:8)',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s raising up of prophets and Nazirites (nazir, H5139 — one consecrated or separated) was an act of covenantal grace and ongoing divine provision within Israel. The Nazirite vow (Num 6:1-21) was a living sign of consecration to YHWH within the community. That Israel silenced these very gifts reveals a rejection of divine governance itself. (1 Sam 3:1; Jer 1:5)',
        13: 'HEBREW: The verb translated "pressing down" (\'uq, H5781) is rare and disputed; some render it "I will make your place narrow" or "I will make you groan." The image of the loaded harvest cart is agricultural and visceral — YHWH\'s judgment does not merely threaten but crushes with irresistible weight. The harvest imagery also carries eschatological resonance in prophetic literature. (Joel 3:13; Rev 14:15)',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: "That day" (yom hahu\') introduces the eschatological horizon of the Day of YHWH, a theme Amos develops extensively (Amos 5:18-20). Even the mightiest warrior flees naked — stripped of all earthly resource and status — before the judgment of YHWH. The total collapse of military might across vv. 14-16 forms a sevenfold pattern, symbolizing complete and inescapable divine retribution. (Amos 5:18; Joel 2:11; Rev 6:15-17)',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The verb "spoken" (dabar, H1696) frames the prophetic oracle as a formal divine lawsuit. The phrase "whole family" (kol-hamishpachah) emphasizes corporate solidarity — the covenant encompasses all Israel, not merely its leadership. THEOLOGICAL: The charge is addressed to the entire covenant community descended from the Exodus, establishing the covenantal basis for the indictment that follows.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Known" (yada, H3045) is not mere cognitive awareness but intimate covenant relationship — the same word used of marriage and deep personal union (Gen 4:1). Israel\'s election intensifies rather than removes accountability. TYPOLOGY: This principle of heightened responsibility for those who have received greater revelation finds its fullest expression in the judgment of those who reject the Messiah (Luke 12:48; Matt 11:20-24).',
        6: 'HEBREW: "Ram\'s horn" translates shofar (H7782), the instrument of alarm and assembly used throughout Israel\'s warfare and liturgy. "Calamity" (ra\'ah, H7451) can mean evil, disaster, or adversity — its range includes both moral evil and consequential judgment. THEOLOGICAL: The rhetorical logic asserts YHWH\'s sovereign governance over all historical catastrophe, a cornerstone of Amos\'s theology of divine judgment.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Secret counsel" (sod, H5475) denotes the intimate deliberative council — the same term used in Ps 89:7 and Jer 23:18, 22 for the divine assembly where YHWH\'s decrees are issued. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Amos here asserts that the prophets are those who have been admitted into the sod of YHWH — they are privy to the decisions of the heavenly council, functioning as YHWH\'s heralds to earth (cf. 1 Kgs 22:19-22; Jer 23:18). This verse is foundational for understanding the prophetic office in its cosmic dimension.',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: Ashdod was a major Philistine city-state; Egypt, a perennial rival and sometime ally of Israel. Both are summoned as witnesses to Samaria\'s corruption — a dramatic irony, since pagan nations are called to testify against the covenant people. THEOLOGICAL: The mountains of Samaria serve as the courtroom setting for this cosmic lawsuit (rib), a common motif in prophetic literature (cf. Mic 6:1-2).',
        11: 'HISTORICAL: The "adversary" (tsur, H6862, lit. "one who presses in" or "enemy") is left unnamed, but Amos\'s audience would recognize this as a veiled reference to Assyria, whose campaigns against the northern kingdom culminated in the fall of Samaria in 722 BC (2 Kgs 17). The prophecy was fulfilled with remarkable precision.',
        12: 'HEBREW: The image of the shepherd salvaging "two legs or a piece of an ear" from a lion\'s kill reflects actual ANE shepherding law — partial remains were presented as proof of a predator\'s attack to exempt the shepherd from financial liability (cf. Exod 22:13). THEOLOGICAL: The rescue language is bitterly ironic: the "remnant" preserved will be pitifully small and stripped of all dignity — fragments rather than deliverance.',
        14: 'HISTORICAL: Bethel (lit. "house of God") was the premier royal sanctuary of the northern kingdom, established by Jeroboam I with golden calves as an alternative to Jerusalem worship (1 Kgs 12:28-29). "Horns of the altar" were projections at each corner considered most sacred — to cut them off was to utterly desecrate and nullify the altar\'s atoning function. TYPOLOGY: The destruction of these false cult sites anticipates the ultimate cleansing of corrupt worship, fulfilled eschatologically in the Messiah who alone is the true altar and sacrifice (Heb 13:10).',
        15: 'HISTORICAL: "Houses of ivory" (battei hashen) are attested archaeologically — ivory inlay panels and furnishings were luxury items of the Israelite elite, confirmed by the Samaria Ivories discovered in excavations of Omride palace quarters. "Winter house" and "summer house" indicate the extreme opulence of the ruling class. THEOLOGICAL: The destruction of luxury estates embodies YHWH\'s judgment against the social injustice funded by the oppression of the poor — a theme Amos will develop through the remainder of the book.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Cows of Bashan" (parot ha-Bashan) is a biting irony — Bashan was renowned for its fat, well-fed cattle (Deut 32:14; Ezek 39:18). The prophet applies this image to the wealthy women of Samaria who lived in ease while exploiting the poor. "Oppress" (ashaq, Strong\'s H6231) denotes crushing economic oppression, often involving the withholding of wages or legal rights. THEOLOGICAL: The accusation that these women commanded their husbands ("lords," adoneihem) to serve their appetites inverts the household order and places social exploitation at the feet of the elite class — a direct covenant violation (Lev 19:13).',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH swears "by His holiness" (b\'qodsho) — one of the most absolute oath formulas in the prophetic corpus, parallel to His swearing "by Himself" (Gen 22:16; Amos 6:8). What is sworn by His essential nature cannot be revoked. HISTORICAL: The imagery of hooks and fishhooks describes deportation practices attested in Assyrian reliefs, where captives were literally led by hooks through the lips or nose — a fitting fulfillment given the Assyrian exile of the Northern Kingdom in 722 B.C. (2 Kgs 17:6).',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: This passage is biting prophetic irony (sarcasm) — YHWH ironically invites Israel to Bethel and Gilgal to "multiply transgression" (pish\'u). Both sites were loaded with covenantal history: Gilgal was where Israel first camped after crossing the Jordan (Josh 4:19); Bethel was where Jacob met God (Gen 28:19). By Amos\'s day both had become centers of syncretistic, illegitimate worship (1 Kgs 12:29). Their religious zeal was real, but it was directed at corrupted institutions, making devotion itself an act of rebellion. TYPOLOGY: This pattern — outward religious observance without justice or covenant faithfulness — is condemned by Christ in Matt 23:23 and echoes throughout the NT prophetic tradition.',
        5: 'HEBREW: "Thank offering" (todah, Strong\'s H8426) derives from the root yadah, meaning to praise or acknowledge. Leavened bread was explicitly forbidden in most offerings (Lev 2:11), making a leavened todah a ritual violation. "Freewill offerings" (nedavot, Strong\'s H5071) were voluntary gifts, but here they are performed as public spectacle. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "for so you love to do" (ki ken ahavtem) is devastatingly ironic — their worship is self-serving performance, not YHWH-directed devotion. True worship and social justice cannot be separated in the prophetic vision (Isa 1:11-17; Mic 6:6-8).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The refrain "yet you did not return to Me" (v\'lo-shavtem adai) appears five times in this chapter (vv. 6, 8, 9, 10, 11), creating a devastating liturgical structure of judgment. Each escalating disaster was a covenant discipline designed to provoke repentance (teshuvah), but Israel refused. HISTORICAL: "Cleanness of teeth" is a vivid idiom for famine — teeth are clean because there is no food to dirty them. This was a covenant curse stipulated in advance (Lev 26:26; Deut 28:48).',
        11: 'HISTORICAL: The comparison to the overthrow of Sodom and Gomorrah (Gen 19:24-25) invokes the most catastrophic divine judgment in Israel\'s memory. The phrase "brand plucked from the burning" (ud mutzal mi\'sreifah) suggests a remnant that barely survived — Israel has been to the edge of annihilation and still has not repented. THEOLOGICAL: This image of a "brand plucked from the burning" is later applied to Joshua the high priest in Zech 3:2, suggesting a typological trajectory of remnant rescue that culminates in redemptive restoration.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Prepare to meet your God" (hikon liqrat Elohecha) is among the most solemn summons in the Old Testament. The verb hikon (from kun, Strong\'s H3559) means to make oneself firm, established, ready — used of ceremonial preparation (Exod 19:11, 15). The meeting envisioned here is not a salvation encounter but a judicial one — Israel is being summoned before the divine court. TYPOLOGY: The language anticipates the eschatological Day of YHWH, in which all nations and peoples will face the divine tribunal (Rev 6:17; Mal 3:2).',
        13: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The closing doxology identifies YHWH as "God of hosts" (Elohei Tseva\'ot, Strong\'s H6635 for tsava) — the commander of the heavenly armies and the divine council. This title situates YHWH\'s judgment not merely as a personal act but as the decree of the supreme sovereign over all cosmic and earthly powers. HEBREW: "Wind" or "spirit" (ruach, Strong\'s H7307) is deliberately ambiguous — YHWH creates both the physical wind and, by extension, the animating breath of all creatures. "Declares to man what is His thought" (maggid l\'adam mah-sicho) emphasizes YHWH\'s condescension in communicating — the prophet himself is the instrument of that divine self-disclosure. STRUCTURE: This is the first of three doxological hymns in Amos (cf. 5:8-9; 9:5-6), each functioning as a cosmic affirmation of YHWH\'s unrivaled sovereignty to anchor the surrounding oracles of judgment.',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The term "lamentation" here is qinah (H7015), a specific genre of funeral dirge with a distinctive 3+2 meter in Hebrew poetry. Amos adopts this genre to declare Israel\'s fate as already accomplished — the prophetic perfect tense renders "she has fallen" as a done deal before it occurs historically. STRUCTURE: This opening sets the elegiac tone for the entire chapter.',
        2: 'TYPOLOGY: The phrase "virgin of Israel" (betulat Yisrael) is a personification of the nation as a young woman who has not yet been conquered — her fall is thus all the more tragic. The image anticipates NT imagery of the Church as the Bride (Rev 19:7) and the profound cost of covenant unfaithfulness. THEOLOGICAL: The absence of a "raiser" echoes the covenant curse language of Leviticus 26.',
        4: 'HEBREW: The verb darash (H1875) means to seek with intentionality, to inquire or resort to. Its use here contrasts the living God with the dead sanctuaries named in verse 5. THEOLOGICAL: The invitation "seek me and live" encapsulates the covenantal gospel embedded in the prophets — life flows from relationship with YHWH, not ritual performance (cf. Deut 4:29; John 5:39-40).',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: Bethel, Gilgal, and Beersheba were all functioning Israelite sanctuaries during the 8th century BC. Bethel was established by Jeroboam I with golden calves (1 Kgs 12:28-29). Gilgal held deep historical memory as Israel\'s first camp in Canaan (Josh 4:19). HEBREW: "Aven" (H205) means wickedness, vanity, or trouble — a wordplay on "Beth-El" (house of God) becoming "Beth-Aven" (house of wickedness), as also used in Hosea 4:15.',
        7: 'HEBREW: Mishpat (H4941) denotes justice in the legal, covenantal, and social sense — the right ordering of community life under YHWH\'s law. Tsedaqah (H6666) is righteousness as right relationship and equitable conduct. Together these two terms form a paired hendiadys central to prophetic ethics throughout the OT (cf. Isa 5:7; Mic 6:8). THEOLOGICAL: Turning justice to "wormwood" (la\'anah) — a bitter, poisonous plant — vividly captures how corruption inverts what should give life.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The doxology in verses 8-9 interrupts the prophetic oracle to ground judgment in the sovereign power of the Creator. YHWH who orders the cosmos (Pleiades = Kimah; Orion = Kesil in Hebrew) is the same one who judges nations. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The naming formula "YHWH is his name" (YHWH shemo) functions as a combat-myth declaration asserting YHWH\'s supremacy over all astral deities associated with these constellations in ANE religion (cf. Job 9:9; 38:31).',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: The accumulation of legal and economic sins — afflicting the righteous, taking bribes, thrusting aside the needy "in the gate" — all relate to the gate as the ancient Israelite courtroom. HISTORICAL: City gates served as the primary locus of judicial proceedings and commerce in Iron Age Israel, making corruption there a direct attack on covenant society (cf. Prov 31:23; Ruth 4:1-2).',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "it may be" (ulay) introduces a remarkable note of divine conditionality and genuine contingency — YHWH\'s relenting is real and not merely rhetorical. HEBREW: "Remnant" (she\'erit, H7611) here first appears in Amos, anticipating the remnant theology that becomes central in Isaiah and Micah. The partial survival of "Joseph" (northern kingdom) points forward to the ingathering of all Israel (cf. Amos 9:11-12; Acts 15:16-17).',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "Day of YHWH" (Yom YHWH) was apparently expected by many in Israel as a day of national vindication against enemies. Amos radically reorients this expectation: the Day will be one of judgment upon Israel itself. This is among the earliest explicit uses of this eschatological concept in the OT. TYPOLOGY: The NT expands the Day of YHWH into the Day of the Lord associated with Christ\'s return (2 Thess 2:2; Rev 6:17).',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s rejection of feasts (chaggim), solemn assemblies (atzarot), burnt offerings, grain offerings, and peace offerings (shelamim) is not an abolition of worship but a condemnation of ritual divorced from covenant ethics and social justice. TYPOLOGY: Jesus cites this prophetic tradition in denouncing hypocritical worship (Matt 15:8-9), and the early church understood authentic worship as inseparable from righteousness (Jas 1:27).',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: Verse 24 is among the most cited verses in biblical prophetic ethics — "let justice roll down like waters." The imagery of a nahal eithan (perennial stream, never going dry) contrasts with the intermittent wadis of the Negev that flood briefly and vanish. TYPOLOGY: Martin Luther King Jr. famously quoted this verse, but its original context demands justice as a permanent structural reality, not a seasonal occurrence, grounded in YHWH\'s own covenantal character.',
        25: 'HISTORICAL: This verse raises the question of the nature of wilderness worship — some scholars see it as a rhetorical question expecting "no" (you did not offer properly), while others read it as irony. The forty years in the wilderness forms the normative baseline for covenant relationship (cf. Jer 7:22-23; Hos 2:14-15). THEOLOGICAL: The point is that YHWH sought loyalty and obedience, not the mechanical offering of sacrifices divorced from the heart.',
        26: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: Sikkuth and Kiyyun are Assyrian astral deities — Sikkuth (Sakkuth) is associated with Saturn/Ninurta, and Kiyyun (Chiun) likewise has Mesopotamian stellar associations. The MT preserves the consonants of these names but vocalizes them with the vowels of shiqquts (abomination) — a scribal polemical device. HISTORICAL: Stephen quotes this verse in Acts 7:42-43 (following the LXX rendering as "Moloch" and "Rephan"), applying it to Israel\'s idolatry as the reason for exile, demonstrating that Amos\'s indictment reached into the NT era.',
        27: 'HISTORICAL: "Beyond Damascus" points toward Assyria, the instrument of YHWH\'s judgment that would indeed exile the northern kingdom in 722/721 BC under Tiglath-Pileser III and Sargon II. THEOLOGICAL: The closing formula "YHWH, the God of hosts (Tseva\'ot)" reasserts divine sovereignty — it is not Assyrian power but YHWH himself who drives the exile, framing judgment within covenant rather than abandonment.',
    },
    6: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: The double "woe" (Hebrew: hoy, H1945) pronounced over both Zion (Judah) and Samaria (Israel) is striking — complacency under divine privilege is condemned equally in both kingdoms. The "notable men of the first of the nations" reflects the self-perception of Israel\'s elite, a pride directly targeted by the oracle. TYPOLOGY: The ease and false security of the complacent elite anticipates NT warnings against spiritual complacency (Rev 3:17, the Laodicean church).',
        3: 'HEBREW: "chamas" (H2555) denotes violence, wrongdoing, and injustice — a weighty term used of the pre-flood corruption (Gen 6:11) and in prophetic indictments of social evil. The phrase "put far away the evil day" reflects a willful suppression of eschatological awareness, a denial of coming judgment. THEOLOGICAL: The drawing near of "the seat of violence" indicates that the elite\'s lifestyle does not merely tolerate injustice but institutionalizes and enthroned it.',
        6: 'HEBREW: "Shever" (H7667) means a breaking, fracture, or collapse — often used of catastrophic national ruin (cf. Isa 1:28; Jer 4:6). The phrase "ruin of Joseph" is a poignant synecdoche for the northern kingdom. THEOLOGICAL: The ultimate indictment is not the luxury itself but the moral insensibility — they are not "grieved" (Hebrew: chalah, to be sick, pained) over the disintegration of the covenant people around them.',
        8: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: YHWH swears "by himself" (Hebrew: b\'nafsho, by his soul/self) — an oath of ultimate divine authority requiring no higher witness (cf. Heb 6:13). HEBREW: "Ge\'on Ya\'akov" (the pride of Jacob, H1347) is a term that elsewhere describes YHWH\'s own majesty (Ps 47:4), making its application to Israel\'s arrogance a devastating irony. "Tseva\'ot" (hosts) underscores YHWH\'s command over the divine armies that will execute this judgment.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: The command "Silence! For we must not mention the name of YHWH" is one of the most theologically dense phrases in Amos. In the context of death and devastation so total that the survivors fear even invoking YHWH\'s name — whether from superstitious terror, shame, or a sense that further divine attention would be catastrophic — it communicates the utter dissolution of covenant relationship. HISTORICAL: The burning of the dead is unusual in Israelite practice, suggesting conditions of plague or mass death so severe that normal burial is impossible.',
        12: 'HEBREW: "Mishpat" (H4941, justice/judgment) and "tsedaqah" (H6666, righteousness) are the twin pillars of covenant social ethics, frequently paired in the prophets (cf. Amos 5:24; Isa 5:7). The rhetorical questions about horses on rock and plowing with oxen establish the unnatural absurdity of Israel\'s moral inversion — perverting the very structures of society is as contrary to nature as these impossible agricultural images.',
        13: 'HISTORICAL: "Lo-debar" (meaning "a thing of nothing" or "no word/thing") and "Karnaim" ("two horns," symbolizing strength) were likely real towns in Transjordan recaptured under Jeroboam II (cf. 2 Kgs 14:25). THEOLOGICAL: Amos weaponizes the place names: Israel boasts in "nothing" (Lo-debar) and attributes to their own "strength" what belongs to YHWH\'s forbearance. The wordplay exposes the theological bankruptcy of nationalist triumphalism.',
        14: 'HISTORICAL: "From Lebo-hamath to the Brook of the Arabah" delineates the full extent of Israel\'s northern and southern borders — the nation at its Jeroboam-era zenith (2 Kgs 14:25) will be oppressed in its entirety. The "nation" raised up is Assyria, whose campaigns under Tiglath-Pileser III (mid-8th century BC) would devastate the northern kingdom. THEOLOGICAL: YHWH as the God of hosts (tseva\'ot) who "raises up" (meqim) a foreign nation is a potent declaration of his sovereignty over all kingdoms of the earth.',
    },
    7: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The term translated "forming" is yotzer (Strong\'s H3335), from the root yatsar, the same verb used of YHWH forming man from the dust (Gen 2:7), carrying creative and sovereign overtones. "Latter growth" (leqesh) refers to the second crop after the first mowing — the king\'s mowing representing a royal tax on first harvests, leaving the people entirely dependent on the second crop, which the locusts then destroy. HISTORICAL: The king\'s mowing as a form of taxation is attested in ANE contexts and underscores the socioeconomic burden already on the poor, a central theme in Amos.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s "relenting" (nacham, Strong\'s H5162) does not imply divine inconsistency or ignorance of the future; rather, it is a relational-covenantal term describing YHWH\'s genuine responsiveness to intercessory prayer. This is a key theme in Mosaic-prophetic intercession (cf. Exod 32:14; Jer 18:8). Amos here functions as a mediator, standing in the gap for a sinful people, foreshadowing the ultimate intercessory work of Messiah (Heb 7:25).',
        7: 'HEBREW: The Hebrew word \'anakh (Strong\'s H594) appears only here in the entire Hebrew Bible, making its precise meaning difficult to establish with certainty. Ancient translations rendered it variously; many modern scholars follow the interpretation "plumb line" based on Akkadian cognates (anaku, "tin" or a measuring instrument). THEOLOGICAL: The plumb line represents the standard of Torah-covenant righteousness against which Israel is measured and found wanting — YHWH\'s judgment is not arbitrary but is grounded in a fixed moral-covenantal norm.',
        9: 'TYPOLOGY: "The high places of Isaac" and "the sanctuaries of Israel" reference the apostate northern cultic system centered at Bethel and Dan (cf. 1 Kgs 12:28-31). The announcement of desolation anticipates the Assyrian destruction of Samaria (722 B.C.). THEOLOGICAL: The specific naming of "the house of Jeroboam" with the sword was fulfilled historically (2 Kgs 14:29; 15:10), demonstrating the precision of prophetic fulfillment and undergirding the canonical authority of Amos.',
        12: 'HEBREW: Amaziah calls Amos a chozeh (Strong\'s H2374), meaning "seer" — one who receives divine visions — rather than nabi ("prophet"). This may carry a dismissive or limiting connotation, as if to classify Amos as merely a visionary rather than a covenantal spokesman. His instruction to "eat bread" in Judah implies Amos was a professional prophet-for-hire, a charge Amos forcefully rejects in verse 14. HISTORICAL: Bethel was the royal sanctuary of the Northern Kingdom, making Amaziah its official state priest — his opposition to Amos represents the institutional religion of the state arrayed against the word of YHWH.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: Amos\'s declaration — "I was no prophet, nor was I the son of a prophet" — is one of the most striking claims of divine call in the Hebrew canon. He explicitly disclaims membership in the professional prophetic guilds (benei ha-nevi\'im), insisting his authority derives solely from YHWH\'s sovereign commission, not institutional credentials. TYPOLOGY: This pattern of the called outsider — shepherd, farmer, fisherman — who speaks divine truth against established religious power prefigures the ministry of Jesus (Matt 4:18-22; John 7:15) and the apostolic pattern of divine calling overriding human qualification (1 Cor 1:26-29).',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: The oracle against Amaziah is structured as a precise counter-judgment: because he silenced the word of YHWH, the word of YHWH pronounces judgment on his house, his family, his land, and his life. The threat that he will "die in an unclean land" — i.e., in Assyrian exile — is particularly devastating for a priest for whom ritual purity and access to the sanctuary were central. HISTORICAL: The prophecy of exile (galah, Strong\'s H1540) for Israel anticipates the Assyrian deportation of 722 B.C. under Sargon II, one of the most thoroughly documented events in both biblical and ANE records, attested in the Sargon II annals from Khorsabad.',
    },
    8: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The "basket of summer fruit" is Hebrew qayits (H7019, ripe/summer fruit). THEOLOGICAL: YHWH employs a wordplay central to the vision: qayits (summer fruit) sounds nearly identical to qets (H7093, "end"), establishing that Israel\'s ripeness for judgment mirrors fruit ripe for picking. This is a classic prophetic pun (paranomasia) leveraging phonetic similarity to communicate theological reality.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "I will never again pass by them" (lo\' osif \'od \'avor lo) signals the termination of divine forbearance. Earlier in Amos (7:8), YHWH had set a plumb line; now the verdict is irrevocable. TYPOLOGY: The language of YHWH "passing by" echoes the Passover and the theophany to Moses (Exod 34:6), suggesting Israel has exhausted the grace afforded by covenant relationship.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "Aniyim" (H6041) denotes the afflicted and economically vulnerable, those bent low by oppression. HISTORICAL: The socioeconomic stratification of 8th-century Israel under Jeroboam II (2 Kgs 14:23-29) produced a merchant class that exploited peasant farmers, as confirmed by Samaria Ostraca (administrative records from c. 780 BC) documenting land consolidation and tax collection.',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: The "ephah" was a dry measure (~22 liters); making it "small" meant cheating buyers on quantity. The "shekel" as a weight standard meant inflating prices by using heavier weights. THEOLOGICAL: Violation of Leviticus 19:35-36 and Deuteronomy 25:13-16 is explicit here — covenant Torah was being deliberately subverted for commercial gain, making religious observance (Sabbath, new moon) a mere inconvenience interrupting profit.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "pride (ge\'on) of Jacob" is deliberately ironic — YHWH swears not by his own name but by the very arrogance of Israel that has occasioned judgment. HEBREW: Ge\'on (H1347) ordinarily denotes the majesty or excellence of YHWH himself (Exod 15:7), but here it is applied with bitter irony to Israel\'s self-exaltation, which YHWH holds up as the very evidence that condemns them.',
        9: 'TYPOLOGY: The darkening of the sun at noon anticipates the cosmic sign at the crucifixion of Yeshua the Messiah, when darkness covered the land from the sixth to the ninth hour (Luke 23:44-45). The reversal of creation order (light becoming darkness at midday) signals divine judgment of the most catastrophic kind. THEOLOGICAL: "That day" (yom hahu) is a recurring eschatological marker in the prophets, pointing beyond the immediate Assyrian crisis to ultimate divine reckoning.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "famine of the word of YHWH" represents perhaps the most severe form of divine judgment — not physical destruction but the withdrawal of prophetic revelation. TYPOLOGY: This passage finds partial fulfillment in the 400 years of prophetic silence between Malachi and John the Baptist, and its full resolution in Yeshua as the incarnate Word (dabar/logos, John 1:14), through whom YHWH spoke his final and definitive word (Heb 1:1-2).',
        12: 'HEBREW: "Dabar" (H1697) is the comprehensive Hebrew term for "word" or "matter," encompassing divine utterance, prophetic oracle, and covenantal communication. THEOLOGICAL: The frantic geographic searching — "from sea to sea, from north to east" — describes a comprehensive and exhausting quest that yields nothing, the tragic irony being that Israel had despised the word when it was freely given through Amos and his contemporaries.',
        14: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "As your god lives, O Dan" is an oath formula invoking the golden calf installed at Dan by Jeroboam I (1 Kgs 12:29), a rival cult center to Jerusalem that embodied Israel\'s covenant infidelity. THEOLOGICAL: "The way of Beer-sheba" likely refers to a pilgrimage practice at the southernmost cult site, suggesting a syncretic religious tourism that mixed YHWH worship with Canaanite forms. The verdict — "they shall fall and rise no more" — is the final and absolute word of this chapter\'s judgment oracle.',
    },
    9: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: The vision of YHWH standing "beside the altar" (not "upon" as in some versions — the Hebrew \'al is ambiguous) signals a divine court judgment scene; the sanctuary itself becomes the site of condemnation. The shaking of thresholds and shattering of capitals echoes the collapse of the cosmos under divine wrath, making escape impossible in every direction (vv. 2-4). TYPOLOGY: The imagery of inescapable divine pursuit anticipates the NT teaching that none can flee the judgment of God (Heb 4:13), while also framing the need for a mediatorial Messiah who absorbs that wrath on behalf of the remnant.',
        3: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "serpent" commanded by YHWH on the floor of the sea recalls the ancient Near Eastern chaos-creature (Leviathan/Tannin) subordinated to YHWH\'s authority. Far from being an autonomous force, the sea-dragon is here depicted as a servant of the divine council\'s sovereign Lord. HEBREW: The Hebrew nachash (H5175) refers to a serpent, likely carrying mythological freight from Canaanite cosmology, where sea-monsters represented primordial chaos; Amos subverts this by making the creature an instrument of YHWH\'s justice.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: This doxology (cf. Amos 4:13; 5:8-9) is one of three hymnic fragments in Amos that assert YHWH\'s cosmic sovereignty. His "upper chambers" (aliyyot, H5944) built in the heavens and His "vault" (aguddah, H92) founded upon the earth depict YHWH as cosmic architect, directly confronting Baalist claims to control of sky and sea. DIVINE_COUNCIL: YHWH\'s summons of sea-waters echoes the defeat of the sea in Canaanite mythology, here appropriated to assert that what Baal allegedly controlled, YHWH actually does — effortlessly and as sovereign Lord.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: This rhetorically explosive verse dismantles Israelite ethnic exceptionalism. YHWH\'s providential governance extends to the migrations of Cushites, Philistines, and Arameans — traditional enemies — placing them on equal footing as objects of divine action in history. HISTORICAL: Caphtor is generally identified with Crete or the Aegean region, aligning with archaeological and textual evidence for the Sea Peoples\' origins. Kir appears in Amos 1:5 as the place of Aram\'s exile, forming a literary inclusio.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The tension between total destruction and preservation of a remnant is the theological hinge of the entire book. YHWH\'s judgment is absolute against the "sinful kingdom" as a political entity, but the "house of Jacob" — the covenant people — contains an indestructible remnant held by divine promise. This distinction between institutional Israel and the true remnant runs throughout the prophets (cf. Rom 9:6).',
        9: 'HEBREW: The kevarah (H3531), a sieve or mesh strainer, is the central metaphor: grain passes through (judgment), but the pebbles — here representing the righteous remnant — do not fall to the earth (are not lost). THEOLOGICAL: This sifting image is directly echoed by Jesus in Luke 22:31, where Satan desires to "sift" Peter like wheat, inverting the metaphor — YHWH\'s sifting preserves the remnant, while the adversary\'s sifting seeks to destroy. The remnant theology of Amos is foundational to NT ecclesiology.',
        11: 'TYPOLOGY: The "fallen booth (sukkah) of David" is the most explicitly messianic text in Amos, directly quoted by James at the Jerusalem Council (Acts 15:16-17) to justify Gentile inclusion in the people of God without full Torah observance. The sukkah (H5521), a temporary shelter, conveys the Davidic dynasty in a state of ruin and collapse — yet YHWH promises its resurrection. THEOLOGICAL: The promise to "raise up" (qum, H6965) the fallen booth anticipates resurrection language; the Davidic covenant, though apparently broken, is not annulled but will be divinely reconstituted in the Messiah (cf. Luke 1:32-33; Rev 3:7).',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: James\'s citation of this verse in Acts 15:17 (following the LXX, which reads "all mankind" rather than "Edom") provided the hermeneutical key for the Jerusalem Council\'s decision on Gentile inclusion. The Hebrew \'Edom\' and \'adam\' (mankind) are textually similar, and the LXX reading may reflect a variant tradition or interpretive tradition. THEOLOGICAL: "Called by My name" (niqra shemi \'alehem) is covenant adoption language — YHWH\'s name placed upon the nations signals universal covenant extension, the fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise that all families of the earth would be blessed (Gen 12:3).',
        13: 'HISTORICAL: The images of overlapping agricultural cycles — the plowman overtaking the reaper — depict eschatological abundance so great that harvesting one crop overlaps with planting the next, an inversion of the curses of Lev 26 and Deut 28. HEBREW: Asis (H6071) refers specifically to freshly pressed, sweet grape juice or wine, connoting the richest first-press of the harvest. The "dripping mountains" echo Joel 3:18, forming an intertextual network of eschatological restoration across the Twelve Prophets.',
        14: 'HEBREW: The phrase shevut (H7622, also shebut) translated "fortunes" or "captivity" is a covenant-restoration formula appearing across the prophets (Jer 30:3; Ezek 39:25; Zeph 3:20). THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s restoration is comprehensively material — cities rebuilt, vineyards planted, gardens cultivated — resisting any purely spiritualized reading of eschatological hope. The return from exile is both historical (the post-exilic return) and typological of the ultimate restoration under Messiah.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The final verse grounds Israel\'s permanent restoration in YHWH\'s own giving of the land — the land is His to give and His promise to preserve. The phrase "never again be uprooted" (lo yinnashu od) is the most absolute promise in the chapter, functioning as the eschatological seal on all prior restoration promises. TYPOLOGY: Read canonically, this "never again" points beyond the post-exilic return (which was partial and temporary) to the Messianic Kingdom, in which the renewed people of God — including believing Gentiles incorporated through the raised booth of David — inherit the new creation (Rev 21-22).',
    },
}